{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011X5y7CkXuqorkDJFkRaRF2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three jobs completed successfully. Here's the summary:\n\n---\n\n## Results Summary\n\n**Cluster:** Spark master + worker both running (`1/1 Ready`), jobs used `local[2]` mode within each pod.\n\n**No configuration bugs were found** — the cluster and job YAMLs were correctly configured. The baseline job was already running when we started and completed normally.\n\n### Performance Comparison\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed | Speedup | Optimization |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Baseline** | 33.6s | 1x (reference) | None — skewed shuffle join |\n| **Broadcast Join** | 14.56s | **2.3x faster** | Broadcasts small `products` table, eliminates shuffle entirely |\n| **AQE** | 15.2s | **2.2x faster** | Auto-splits hot partitions at runtime (`skewJoin.enabled=true`) |\n\n### Data Skew Observed\n- Actual skew ratio: **44x** (max partition 11,579 rows vs min 263 rows)\n- Hot products 1–5 caused 5 of 20 partitions to hold ~50% of all orders\n- Baseline straggler partitions dominated total query time\n\n### Why the optimizations work\n- **Broadcast join**: The `products` table (100 rows) is tiny — broadcasting it to every executor means each executor does a local lookup instead of a costly hash-shuffle on the skewed `product_id` key.\n- **AQE**: Spark 3.x's Adaptive Query Execution detects skewed partitions at runtime and automatically splits them into sub-tasks, distributing the hot-partition work across multiple executors.\n\nBoth strategies achieved nearly identical ~2.3x improvement. For this workload, broadcast join is the preferred choice since the dimension table is small and statically known."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":177,"cache_read_input_tokens":43064,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_token